1 b. The institution of revocation or suspension proceedings against the
2 licensee by any State or governmental agency.
3 c. Any felony indictment of the licensee or any control person related to
4 student loan servicing activities.
5 d. Any felony conviction of the licensee or any control person related to
6 student loan servicing activities.
7 (3) If the information contained in any document filed with the Commissioner or
8 the NMLS is or becomes inaccurate or incomplete in any material respect, the
9 licensee or applicant shall within 30 days file a correcting amendment to the
10 information contained in the document.
11 (b) Annual Report on Student Loans. – No later than 90 days after the end of the calendar
12 year, a licensee shall file an annual report in a form prescribed by the Commissioner through the
13 NMLS. The report shall include all of the following relating to student loans serviced by the
14 licensee on behalf of borrowers in this State:
15 (1) The number of borrowers, number of student loans, and total outstanding
16 balance.
17 (2) With respect to student loans enrolled in any type of income-driven repayment
18 plan, the number of borrowers, number of student loans, and total outstanding
19 balance.
20 (3) The types of student loans, such as federal, private, Federal Family Education
21 Loan (FFEL), Parent Plus, Perkins, and institutional loans, and the number of
22 student loans for each type.
23 (4) The number of student loans in default, along with a breakdown of the total
24 number of student loans 30 to 90 days delinquent, 91 to 180 days delinquent,
25 and 181 to 270 days delinquent.
26 (5) Any other information deemed relevant by the Commissioner.
27 "§ 53-450. Duties of student loan servicer to borrowers.
28 (a) A student loan servicer shall respond to a written inquiry from a borrower or the
29 representative of a borrower within 10 days of receipt of the request and, within 30 days after the
30 receipt of the request, shall provide information relating to the request and, if applicable, the
31 action the student loan servicer will take to correct the borrower's account or an explanation for
32 why the student loan servicer believes the account is correct.
33 (b) The 30-day period in subsection (a) of this section may be extended for not more than
34 15 days if, before the end of the 30-day period, the student loan servicer notifies the borrower or
35 the borrower's representative of the extension and the reason for the delay.
36 (c) Except when required by 15 U.S.C. § 1692e(8) to communicate that a debt is disputed,
37 a student loan servicer shall not furnish to a consumer reporting agency information regarding a
38 payment that is the subject of a written inquiry related to a dispute on a borrower's payment on a
39 student loan during the 60 days following receipt of the written inquiry. A student loan servicer,
40 however, may furnish to a consumer reporting agency information regarding the disputed
41 payment after this period of time, even if the borrower submits an additional written inquiry.
42 (d) Except as provided in federal law or required by a student loan agreement, a student
43 loan servicer shall inquire of a borrower how to apply an overpayment to a student loan. A
44 borrower's direction on how to apply an overpayment to a student loan stays in effect for any
45 future overpayments during the term of the loan until the borrower provides different directions.
46 (e) A student loan servicer shall apply partial payments in a manner that minimizes late
47 fees and negative credit reporting. Where loans on a borrower's student loan account have an
48 equal level of delinquency, a student loan servicer shall apply partial payments to satisfy as many
49 individual loan payments as possible on the borrower's account.
DRS45219-MUf-38 Page 7

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (f) In the event of the sale, assignment, or other transfer of the servicing of a student loan
2 that results in a change in the identity of the person to which a borrower is required to send
3 payments or direct any communication concerning the loan, the following provisions apply:
4 (1) The new student loan servicer shall honor all benefits originally represented
5 as available during repayment, including those for which the borrower has not
6 yet qualified.
7 (2) The old student loan servicer shall transfer all records of the borrower to the
8 new student loan servicer within 45 days of the sale, assignment, or transfer.
9 (3) The new student loan servicer shall provide notice to the borrower of the sale,
10 assignment, or transfer at least seven days before the first payment is due to
11 the new student loan servicer. The notice shall include the identity of the new
12 student loan servicer, the effective date of the sale, assignment, or transfer, the
13 date the old student loan servicer will no longer accept payments, and the
14 contact information for the new student loan servicer.
15 (g) Except as otherwise provided in federal law, federal student loan agreements, or a
16 contract between the federal government and a student loan servicer, a student loan servicer shall
17 properly evaluate a borrower for an income-based repayment program, public service loan
18 forgiveness program, or other repayment program before placing the borrower in forbearance or
19 default if one or more of these programs is available to the borrower.
20 "§ 53-451. Prohibited conduct.
21 In addition to the activities prohibited under other provisions of this Article, it is unlawful for
22 any student loan servicer to do any of the following:
23 (1) Directly or indirectly employ a scheme, device, or artifice to defraud or
24 mislead borrowers or the Commissioner.
25 (2) Engage in an unfair or deceptive trade practice toward any person or
26 misrepresent or omit any material information in connection with the
27 servicing of a student loan, including the amount, nature, or terms of any fee
28 or payment due or claimed to be due on a student loan, the terms and
29 conditions of the loan agreement, or the borrower's obligation under the
30 student loan.
31 (3) Obtain property by fraud or misrepresentation.
32 (4) Misapply payments to the outstanding balance of a student loan.
33 (5) Provide inaccurate information to a consumer reporting agency.
34 (6) Fail to report both the favorable and unfavorable payment history of a
35 borrower to a consumer reporting agency at least annually if the student loan
36 servicer regularly reports information to a consumer reporting agency.
37 (7) Refuse to communicate with an authorized representative of a borrower who
38 provides any written authorization signed by the borrower. The student loan
39 servicer, however, may adopt procedures reasonably related to verifying that
40 the representative is in fact authorized to act on behalf of the borrower. For
41 purposes of this subdivision, a borrower who has submitted a complaint to any
42 State agency is deemed to have authorized the student loan servicer to
43 communicate directly with the State agency about the borrower's student loan.
44 (8) Fail to respond to a communication from any State agency within 20 days or
45 within a shorter reasonable period of time if requested by the State agency.
46 (9) Fail to respond within 20 days to a complaint submitted to the student loan
47 servicer by the Commissioner or Student Loan Ombudsman. If necessary, the
48 student loan servicer may request additional time to respond to the complaint,
49 up to a maximum of 45 days, so long as the request is accompanied by an
50 explanation for why additional time is reasonable and necessary.
