4 systems, methods, or software.
5 (4) Accept and rely on investigation and examination reports made by other
6 governmental agencies.
7 (5) Accept an audit report made by an independent certified public accountant
8 and incorporate the audit report in the report of the investigation or
9 examination or other writing of the Commissioner.
10 (f) The Commissioner may take any action described in G.S. 53-455 or G.S. 53-456,
11 including summary suspension of the license, if a student loan servicer fails within 20 days, or a
12 lesser time if requested for good cause, to do any of the following:
13 (1) Respond to inquiries from the Commissioner regarding any complaint filed
14 against the student loan servicer that appears to involve a violation of this
15 Article or any rule adopted or order issued under this Article.
16 (2) Respond to and cooperate fully with notices from the Commissioner relating
17 to the scheduling and conducting of an investigation or examination.
18 (3) Consent to a criminal history record check. The refusal constitutes grounds
19 for the Commissioner to deny licensure to the applicant as well as any person
20 controlled by the applicant.
21 "§ 53-453. Confidentiality.
22 (a) All information obtained by the Commissioner under this Article is subject to
23 confidential treatment as provided in G.S. 53C-2-7.
24 (b) Notwithstanding any State law to the contrary, the Commissioner shall report
25 enforcement actions under this Article and any other relevant information to the NMLS.
26 (c) The Commissioner may enter into written agreements with other governmental
27 agencies, the Conference of State Bank Supervisors, or other associations representing
28 governmental agencies and may share otherwise confidential information pursuant to these
29 agreements.
30 (d) The requirements of G.S. 53C-2-7 regarding the privacy or confidentiality of any
31 information provided under subsections (b) and (c) of this section, and any privilege arising under
32 any other federal or State law with respect to the information, continues to apply to the
33 information after it has been disclosed to an entity described in subsection (b) or (c) of this
34 section. Information held by the entity is not subject to disclosure under any State law governing
35 the disclosure to the public of information held by an officer or agency of the State. The entities
36 described in subsection (b) or (c) of this section may share information with all State and federal
37 regulatory officials with student loan industry oversight authority without the loss of privilege or
38 the loss of confidentiality protections provided by State and federal law.
39 (e) Nothing in this section prohibits the Commissioner from releasing to the public a list
40 of persons licensed under this Article or aggregated financial data on these licensees.
41 "§ 53-454. Regulatory authority.
42 (a) Unless otherwise provided, all actions, hearings, and procedures under this Article
43 are governed by Article 3A of Chapter 150B of the General Statutes.
44 (b) Upon the issuance of any summary order permitted under this Article, including
45 summary suspensions and cease and desist orders, the Commissioner shall promptly notify the
46 licensee that the order has been entered and the reasons for the order. Within 20 days of receiving
47 notice of the order, the licensee may request in writing a hearing before the Commissioner. The
48 Commissioner shall schedule a hearing within 15 days of receiving the request. If the licensee
49 does not request a hearing, the order remains in effect unless it is modified or vacated by the
50 Commissioner.
51 "§ 53-455. Disciplinary action.
Page 10 DRS45219-MUf-38

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (a) The Commissioner may, by order, deny, suspend, revoke, or refuse to renew a license
2 under this Article or may restrict the manner in which a licensee or a controlling person of a
3 licensee engages in student loan servicing, if the Commissioner finds both of the following:
4 (1) The order is in the public interest.
5 (2) The licensee or a controlling person of the licensee has done or is subject to
6 any of the following:
7 a. Submitted an application for licensure, report, or other document to
8 the Commissioner that, as of its effective date or later, contained a
9 statement that, in light of the circumstances under which it was made,
10 is false or misleading with respect to a material fact.
11 b. Violated any provision of this Article or rule adopted or order issued
12 under this Article.
13 c. Is permanently or temporarily enjoined by a court from engaging in
14 student loan servicing.
15 d. Is the subject of an order entered within the past five years by any
16 governmental agency with jurisdiction over the student loan servicing
17 industry.
18 (b) If the Commissioner has reason to believe that a licensee has violated any provision
19 of this Article or rule adopted or order issued under this Article, the Commissioner may take any
20 of the following actions:
21 (1) Summarily order the licensee to cease and desist from any harmful activities
22 or violations of this Article.
23 (2) Summarily suspend the license of the licensee.
24 This subsection supplements the Commissioner's authority under G.S. 150B-3(c).
25 (c) If a licensee is accused of any act or omission that would subject the licensee to
26 disciplinary action under this section, the licensee, with the approval of the Commissioner, may
27 surrender the license and all of the rights and privileges pertaining to it. A person that surrenders
28 a license is not eligible for licensure under this Article during any period specified by the
29 Commissioner.
30 "§ 53-456. Civil penalty; restitution; disgorgement; authority to prohibit certain conduct.
31 (a) Civil Penalty. – The Commissioner may assess a civil penalty against a student loan
32 servicer not to exceed twenty-five thousand dollars ($25,000) for each violation of this Article,
33 rules adopted under this Article, or order of the Commissioner issued under this Article. The
34 clear proceeds of civil penalties imposed pursuant to this section shall be remitted to the Civil
35 Penalty and Forfeiture Fund in accordance with G.S. 115C-457.2.
36 (b) Restitution. – If a student loan servicer violates this Article or rule adopted or order
37 issued under this Article, the Commissioner may order the student loan servicer to pay restitution
38 to a borrower injured by the violation.
39 (c) Disgorgement. – The Commissioner may require a student loan servicer to disgorge
40 and pay to the borrower or other person any amount received by the student loan servicer
41 collected in violation of Chapter 24 of the General Statutes.
42 (d) Authority to Prohibit. – The Commissioner may prohibit a student loan servicer from
43 engaging in acts or practices in connection with student loan servicing that the Commissioner
44 finds to be unfair, deceptive, designed to evade the laws of this State, or not in the best interest
45 of the borrowing public.
46 "§ 53-457. Civil remedy.
47 (a) A borrower may bring a civil action for damages against a student loan servicer for
48 an injury caused by the student loan servicer's violation of this Article or rule adopted or order
49 issued under this Article. If the violation occurs in connection with the sale, assignment, or other
50 transfer of the servicing between two student loan servicers, the student loan servicers remain
51 jointly and severally liable for the injury.
DRS45219-MUf-38 Page 11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (b) A violation of this Article or rule adopted or order issued under this Article is an
2 unfair or deceptive trade practice for purposes of Chapter 75 of the General Statutes. Nothing in
3 this Article limits any claim otherwise arising under G.S. 75-1.1.
4 "§ 53-458. Service of process.
5 (a) A licensee under this Article is deemed to have done both of the following:
6 (1) Consented to the jurisdiction of the courts of this State for an action arising
7 under this Article.
8 (2) Appointed the Secretary of State as the licensee's agent for the purpose of
9 accepting service of process in an action arising under this Article.
10 (b) The Commissioner is deemed to have complied with the requirement of law
11 concerning service of process upon mailing by certified mail notice to a licensee, postage prepaid
12 and addressed to the last known address on file with the Commissioner.
13 "§ 53-459. Rules; appeal by aggrieved person.
14 (a) The Commissioner may adopt any rule that the Commissioner deems necessary to
15 carry out the provisions of this Article.
16 (b) Pursuant to G.S. 53C-2-6(b), any person aggrieved by any rule adopted or order
17 issued by the Commissioner may appeal to the State Banking Commission for review upon
18 providing a written notice of appeal within 20 days after the rule was adopted or order was issued.
19 The notice of appeal shall specifically state the grounds for appeal and, in the case of an appeal
20 from a contested case proceeding before the Commissioner, shall set forth in numbered order the
21 assignments of error for review by the State Banking Commission. Failure to specify the
22 assignments of error or failure to comply with the briefing schedule provided by the State
23 Banking Commission constitutes grounds to dismiss the appeal. Any party aggrieved by a
24 decision of the State Banking Commission may petition for judicial review pursuant to
25 G.S. 53C-2-6(b).
26 "§ 53-460. Commissioner's participation in nationwide registry.
27 A student loan servicer shall be licensed through the NMLS. In order to carry out this
28 requirement, the Commissioner may participate in the NMLS. G.S. 53-244.119 applies to this
29 section."
30 SECTION 1.(b) This section becomes effective June 1, 2026.
31 SECTION 2.(a) Article 26 of Chapter 53 of the General Statutes, as enacted by this
32 act, is amended by adding the following new sections to read:
33 "§ 53-461. Student Loan Ombudsman.
34 The Commissioner of Banks shall designate a Student Loan Ombudsman to carry out the
35 duties and activities set forth in this Article. The Ombudsman shall provide timely assistance to
36 any borrower of a student loan in this State.
37 "§ 53-462. Duties of the Ombudsman; education course; reports.
38 (a) The Commissioner of Banks shall ensure that the Ombudsman does all of the
39 following:
40 (1) Receives, reviews, and responds to any complaint from a student loan
41 borrower.
42 (2) Provides copies of complaints to the Attorney General, subject to
43 G.S. 53C-2-7.
44 (3) Compiles and analyzes data on student loan borrower complaints.
45 (4) Monitors and analyzes the development and implementation of federal, State,
46 and local laws and policies relating to student loan borrowers and recommends
47 any necessary changes to these laws and policies.
48 (5) Disseminates information concerning the Ombudsman's duties and the
49 regulatory duties of the Commissioner of Banks to institutions of higher
50 education, student loan servicers, and any other appropriate persons.
51 (6) Takes any other action necessary to fulfill the duties set forth in this section.
Page 12 DRS45219-MUf-38

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (b) No later than July 1, 2027, the Office of the Commissioner of Banks, in coordination
2 with the State Education Assistance Authority, shall ensure that the Ombudsman establishes and
3 maintains a student loan borrower education course that includes educational presentations and
4 materials regarding student loans. The program shall include key loan terms, documentation
5 requirements, monthly payment obligations, income-based repayment options, the availability of
6 State and federal loan forgiveness programs, and disclosure requirements.
7 (c) No later than 12 months following the date of appointment of the Ombudsman and
8 annually thereafter, the Ombudsman shall submit a report to the General Assembly regarding all
9 of the following:
10 (1) The implementation of this section, including data collected and analyzed.
11 (2) The overall effectiveness of the Ombudsman position.
12 (3) The efficacy of the student loan borrower education course in making student
13 borrowers aware of their rights and responsibilities and the resources available
14 to them."
15 SECTION 2.(b) This section becomes effective January 1, 2027.
16 SECTION 3. If any provision of this act or its application to any person or
17 circumstance is held invalid, the invalidity does not affect other provisions or applications of this
18 act that can be given effect without the invalid provision or application and, to this end, the
19 provisions of this act are severable.
20 SECTION 4. Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective when it becomes
21 law.
